radius

Baseline Widely available

This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions. It’s been available
across browsers since July 2015 .

-   Learn more
-   <L=2c#6>See full compatibility</L>
-   Report feedback

The  radius  attribute represents the radius (or radii) for the operation on a given
<L=3R> <feMorphology> </L> filter primitive.

If two numbers are provided, the first number represents the x-radius and the second one the y-radius. If
one number is provided, then that value is used for both x and y. The values are in the coordinate system
established by the <L=2a> primitiveUnits </L> attribute on the <L=3Y> <filter> </L> element.

A negative or zero value disables the effect of the given filter primitive (i.e., the result is the
filter input image).

You can use this attribute with the following SVG elements:

-   <L=3R> <feMorphology> </L>

<L=2c#4>Usage notes</L><I=4>
  --------------- -------------------------------------
  Value           <L=3#h><number-optional-number></L>
  Default value    0 
  Animatable      Yes
  --------------- -------------------------------------

<L=2c#5>Specifications</L><I=5>
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Specification
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Filter Effects Module Level 1
  # element-attrdef-femorphology-radius

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

<L=2c#6>Browser compatibility</L><I=6>
This page was last modified on Mar 18, 2025 by MDN contributors .

</B>
